  <!-- LESSON 2: Tier 1 vs Tier 2 Visual Rules        -->
  <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
  <section id="tier-visual-rules" data-slide-index="1" data-lesson-slug="tier-visual-rules" class="module-section py-16">
    <h2>Tier 1 vs Tier 2 Visual Rules</h2>

    <p class="text-lg text-n600 mb-6">
      The two tiers don't just differ in content — they differ in visual treatment. Both use the same design system, but with very different levels of restraint.
    </p>

    <h3 id="tier-1-entertainment-literacy">Tier 1: Entertainment literacy</h3>

    <p>
      Tier 1 content is the majority (~95%) of Playbook output. It should be visually engaging, dynamic, and brand-forward — full color palette, rich layouts, photography, animation, and personality. Here's what that looks like in practice:
    </p>

    <div class="my-6 grid grid-cols-2 gap-4">
      <button class="collateral-lightbox rounded-xl overflow-hidden border border-n100 shadow-sm text-left hover:shadow-md hover:border-teal/30 transition-all cursor-zoom-in group" data-src={`${base}/images/collateral/card-1a-hot-streak.png`} data-title="Tier 1 — Social Card: Myth-buster campaign">
        <img src={`${base}/images/collateral/card-1a-hot-streak.png`} alt="Tier 1 social card — Myth vs Math hot streak campaign" class="w-full group-hover:scale-[1.02] transition-transform" />
        <div class="px-3 py-2 bg-white">
          <p class="text-xs font-heading font-semibold text-navy">Social Card</p>
          <p class="text-xs text-n500">Myth-buster campaign</p>
        </div>
      </button>
      <button class="collateral-lightbox rounded-xl overflow-hidden border border-n100 shadow-sm text-left hover:shadow-md hover:border-teal/30 transition-all cursor-zoom-in group" data-src={`${base}/images/collateral/card-2a-house-edge.png`} data-title="Tier 1 — Education Card: Real odds breakdown">
        <img src={`${base}/images/collateral/card-2a-house-edge.png`} alt="Tier 1 education card — House edge comparison across games" class="w-full group-hover:scale-[1.02] transition-transform" />
        <div class="px-3 py-2 bg-white">
          <p class="text-xs font-heading font-semibold text-navy">Education Card</p>
          <p class="text-xs text-n500">Real odds breakdown</p>
        </div>
      </button>
    </div>

    <p>
      Notice the shared DNA: navy backgrounds, teal accents, Inter headings, the PlayBOOK wordmark, orange for attention. Tier 1 templates span social cards, story formats, posters, emails, venue signage, rack cards, and digital displays — each designed to compete with the operator's best commercial content.
    </p>

    <h3 id="tier-2-support-and-crisis">Tier 2: Support and crisis</h3>

    <p>
      Tier 2 is where visual restraint becomes critical. The design goal is <strong>zero friction</strong> — nothing competes with the support information. Compare these with the Tier 1 examples above:
    </p>

    <div class="my-6 grid grid-cols-2 gap-4">
      <button class="collateral-lightbox rounded-xl overflow-hidden border border-n100 shadow-sm text-left hover:shadow-md hover:border-teal/30 transition-all cursor-zoom-in group" data-src={`${base}/images/collateral/card-tier2-10f.png`} data-title="Tier 2 — Support Card: Clean, sparse, direct">
        <img src={`${base}/images/collateral/card-tier2-10f.png`} alt="Tier 2 support card — clean white layout with prominent helpline number" class="w-full group-hover:scale-[1.02] transition-transform" />
        <div class="px-3 py-2 bg-white">
          <p class="text-xs font-heading font-semibold text-navy">Support Card</p>
          <p class="text-xs text-n500">Clean, sparse, direct</p>
        </div>
      </button>
      <button class="collateral-lightbox rounded-xl overflow-hidden border border-n100 shadow-sm text-left hover:shadow-md hover:border-teal/30 transition-all cursor-zoom-in group" data-src={`${base}/images/collateral/support-page-10a.png`} data-title="Tier 2 — Support Page: Large targets, single column">
        <img src={`${base}/images/collateral/support-page-10a.png`} alt="Tier 2 support page — call, text, chat options with large touch targets" class="w-full group-hover:scale-[1.02] transition-transform" />
        <div class="px-3 py-2 bg-white">
          <p class="text-xs font-heading font-semibold text-navy">Support Page</p>
          <p class="text-xs text-n500">Large targets, single column</p>
        </div>
      </button>
    </div>

    <p>
      The contrast is deliberate: strip back to essentials, maximum contrast, no decorative elements, minimal color, large touch targets, and <strong>always light mode</strong> — dark mode can feel isolating in crisis contexts.</p>

    <p class="font-heading font-semibold text-navy text-lg mt-6 mb-2">Visual elements comparison</p>

    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Element</th>
          <th>Tier 1 treatment</th>
          <th>Tier 2 treatment</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Color</strong></td>
          <td>Full palette, rich combinations</td>
          <td>Neutral + teal only, maximum contrast</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Typography</strong></td>
          <td>Full type scale, varied weights</td>
          <td>Large, clear, minimal hierarchy</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Layout</strong></td>
          <td>Dynamic grids, cards, visual variety</td>
          <td>Single column, generous spacing</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Imagery</strong></td>
          <td>Photography, illustration, data viz</td>
          <td>None. Text and links only.</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <p class="font-heading font-semibold text-navy text-lg mt-6 mb-2">Interaction and mode comparison</p>

    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Element</th>
          <th>Tier 1 treatment</th>
          <th>Tier 2 treatment</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Interaction</strong></td>
          <td>Quizzes, tools, animations</td>
          <td>Simple buttons. No steps. No friction.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Tone</strong></td>
          <td>Playful, confident, witty</td>
          <td>Warm, direct, serious. Zero cleverness.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Dark mode</strong></td>
          <td>Follows system preference</td>
          <td>Always light mode</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <KeyTakeaway>
      <p>
        Both tiers use the same brand quality. The difference is restraint, not quality. Tier 2 isn't "uglier Tier 1" — it's deliberately sparse because visual noise is friction when someone needs help.
      </p>
    </KeyTakeaway>
  </section>

