  <!-- LESSON 3: Accessibility Requirements           -->
  <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
  <section id="accessibility-requirements" data-slide-index="2" data-lesson-slug="accessibility-requirements" class="module-section py-16">
    <h2>Accessibility Requirements</h2>

    <p class="text-lg text-n600 mb-6">
      Accessibility isn't a nice-to-have. If a player can't access your content because of a disability, a device limitation, or a situational constraint (bright sunlight, noisy venue), your education content fails them the same way buried compliance text does. Different barrier, same result: the player doesn't get the information they need.
    </p>

    <h3 id="wcag-21-aa-the-recommended-baseline">WCAG 2.1 AA: the recommended baseline</h3>

    <p>
      Every Playbook touchpoint should meet <Glossary term="WCAG" definition="Web Content Accessibility Guidelines — international standards for making web content accessible to people with disabilities" /> 2.1 AA. Here's what that means in practice:
    </p>

    <p class="font-heading font-semibold text-navy text-lg mt-6 mb-2">Visual requirements</p>

    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Requirement</th>
          <th>Standard</th>
          <th>What it means</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Color contrast (text)</strong></td>
          <td>4.5:1 for normal text, 3:1 for large text</td>
          <td>All foreground/background text combinations must be measurably readable</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Color contrast (UI)</strong></td>
          <td>3:1 for components and graphical objects</td>
          <td>Buttons, icons, charts, and controls must be distinguishable from their backgrounds</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Touch targets</strong></td>
          <td>Minimum 44x44px</td>
          <td>All interactive elements — buttons, links, form fields — must be easily tappable</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <p class="font-heading font-semibold text-navy text-lg mt-6 mb-2">Structural and interaction requirements</p>

    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Requirement</th>
          <th>Standard</th>
          <th>What it means</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Keyboard navigation</strong></td>
          <td>All interactive content must be keyboard-accessible</td>
          <td>Tab order makes sense. Focus states are visible. No keyboard traps.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Screen reader support</strong></td>
          <td>Semantic HTML, ARIA labels where needed</td>
          <td>Content structure is clear to assistive technology</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Text sizing</strong></td>
          <td>Minimum 16px (1rem) body text</td>
          <td>No exceptions. Content people should read must be readable.</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <div class="my-6 rounded-xl border border-n100 bg-white shadow-sm p-5">
      <p class="font-heading font-semibold text-navy text-sm mb-4">Contrast ratio in practice</p>
      <div class="grid grid-cols-2 sm:grid-cols-4 gap-3">
        <div class="rounded-lg overflow-hidden">
          <div class="bg-navy p-3 text-center">
            <p class="text-white text-sm font-heading font-semibold">White on Navy</p>
            <p class="text-teal text-xs font-mono mt-1">13.5:1 ✓</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="rounded-lg overflow-hidden">
          <div class="bg-navy p-3 text-center">
            <p class="text-teal text-sm font-heading font-semibold">Teal on Navy</p>
            <p class="text-teal text-xs font-mono mt-1">7.2:1 ✓</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="rounded-lg overflow-hidden border border-n100">
          <div class="bg-white p-3 text-center">
            <p class="text-navy text-sm font-heading font-semibold">Navy on White</p>
            <p class="text-teal text-xs font-mono mt-1">13.5:1 ✓</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="rounded-lg overflow-hidden border-2 border-danger/30">
          <div class="p-3 text-center" style="background:#E8E8F0">
            <p class="text-sm font-heading font-semibold" style="color:#A8A8C0">Light on Light</p>
            <p class="text-xs font-mono mt-1" style="color:#FF3D00">1.4:1 ✗</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <KeyConcept title="WCAG 2.1 AA Is the Floor">
      <p>4.5:1 contrast for normal text, 3:1 for large text, 44x44px minimum touch targets, full keyboard navigation, and screen reader support. These are non-negotiable — if your contrast fails, your content fails the people who need it most.</p>
    </KeyConcept>

    <KeyTakeaway>
      Accessibility is a prerequisite, not a feature. WCAG 2.1 AA sets the minimum bar: sufficient contrast, tappable targets, keyboard access, and screen reader support. If a player can't reach the information, it doesn't matter how good the content is.
    </KeyTakeaway>
  </section>

